Q: Declarative net request rule.json is not working A: <p>There are several problems.</p>
<ol>
<li><p><code>regexFilter</code> doesn't support JS RegExp literal syntax.</p>
<p>Solution: Remove <code>/</code> and the <code>i</code> flag.</p>
</li>
<li><p><code>regexFilter</code> is for the URL of the request, not for a header name. Currently there's no way to match requests by checking a header.</p>
<p>Solution: Remove <code>regexFilter</code> or use a valid expression for the URL or use other types of conditions like <code>urlFilter</code> or <code>requestDomains</code>, see the <a href="https://developer.chrome.com/docs/extensions/reference/declarativeNetRequest/#type-RuleCondition" rel="nofollow noreferrer">documentation</a>.</p>
</li>
<li><p><code>&quot;header&quot;: &quot;script-src&quot;</code> should be <code>&quot;header&quot;: &quot;content-security-policy&quot;</code></p>
</li>
</ol>
<p>Example:</p>
<pre class="lang-json prettyprint-override"><code>[{
  &quot;id&quot;: 1,
  &quot;action&quot;: {
    &quot;type&quot;: &quot;modifyHeaders&quot;,
    &quot;responseHeaders&quot;: [{
      &quot;header&quot;: &quot;content-security-policy&quot;,
      &quot;operation&quot;: &quot;set&quot;,
      &quot;value&quot;: &quot;script-src https://localhost:7000&quot;
    }]
  },
  &quot;condition&quot;: {
    &quot;requestDomains&quot;: [&quot;example.com&quot;],
    &quot;resourceTypes&quot;: [&quot;main_frame&quot;, &quot;sub_frame&quot;]
  }
}]
</code></pre>
<p>P.S. To change <code>script-src</code> it's sufficient to process <code>main_frame</code> and <code>sub_frame</code> types.</p>

Q: Best way to repeat &lt;slot&gt; content in a custom element A: <p>There is <em>sort of</em> a solution. By setting the <em>slotAssignment</em> option to <em>manual</em> when calling <em>attachShadow</em> <code>this.attachShadow({slotAssignment: &quot;manual&quot;})</code> you can declare that you will be monitoring the nodes and assigning them to slots.</p>
<p>A common pattern is to use an observer to monitor child nodes and then, for each relevant child, create the necessary wrapper elements with a slot inside. You would then call <code>slot.assign(node)</code> and add the wrapper elements to your shadow dom.</p>
<p>This works for the immediate concept but has a pitfall when it comes to reusability inside of other reusable components.</p>
<p>If someone is authoring a component (<em>my-component</em>) that contains a <em>my-list</em> that they want users to be able to populate.</p>
<p>A desired use case might look like:</p>
<pre><code>&lt;my-component&gt;
    &lt;h1&gt;Fruit&lt;h1&gt;
    &lt;div slot=&quot;list-items&quot;&gt;Apple&lt;/div&gt;
    &lt;div slot=&quot;list-items&quot;&gt;Banana&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;/my-component&gt;
</code></pre>
<p>And the desired shadow dom template for <em>my-component</em> might look like:</p>
<pre><code>&lt;template&gt;
    &lt;div id=&quot;header&quot;&gt;&lt;slot&gt;&lt;/slot&gt;&lt;div&gt;
    &lt;my-list&gt;
        &lt;slot name=&quot;list-items&quot;&gt;&lt;/slot&gt;
    &lt;/my-list&gt;
&lt;/template&gt;
</code></pre>
<p>What happens with our earlier approach of observing <em>my-list</em>s children and wrapping each item, is that the children of <em>my-list</em> consist of that singular slot element. Both <em>Apple</em> and <em>Banana</em> would end up placed within a single list item.</p>
<p>Now, you may think, OK, I'll look for slots as well and flatten the assigned nodes.</p>
<p>That won't work. Nodes can only be assigned to one slot at any given point in time, and trying to reassign them will fail silently.</p>
<p>This is because an html element can only appear at one place in the dom at once, but, unfortunately, it also means that, as of the point of writing, there is no way to separate the nodes that have been assigned to the slot.</p>
<p>Without some way of forwarding slotted nodes to separate slots from within <em>my-list</em>, the only way to produce the desired behavior is for <em>my-component</em> to <em>also</em> use manual slot assignment. And so on down the chain.</p>
